<script>// Pandoc 2.9 adds attributes on both header and div. We remove the former (to
// be compatible with the behavior of Pandoc < 2.8).
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function(e) {
  var hs = document.querySelectorAll("div.section[class*='level'] > :first-child");
  var i, h, a;
  for (i = 0; i < hs.length; i++) {
    h = hs[i];
    if (!/^h[1-6]$/i.test(h.tagName)) continue;  // it should be a header h1-h6
    a = h.attributes;
    while (a.length > 0) h.removeAttribute(a[0].name);
  }
});

<script>

/**
 * jQuery Plugin: Sticky Tabs
 *
 * @author Aidan Lister <aidan@php.net>
 * adapted by Ruben Arslan to activate parent tabs too
 * http://www.aidanlister.com/2014/03/persisting-the-tab-state-in-bootstrap/
 */
(function($) {
  "use strict";
  $.fn.rmarkdownStickyTabs = function() {
    var context = this;
    // Show the tab corresponding with the hash in the URL, or the first tab
    var showStuffFromHash = function() {
      var hash = window.location.hash;
      var selector = hash ? 'a[href="' + hash + '"]' : 'li.active > a';
      var $selector = $(selector, context);
      if($selector.data('toggle') === "tab") {
        $selector.tab('show');
        // walk up the ancestors of this element, show any hidden tabs
        $selector.parents('.section.tabset').each(function(i, elm) {
          var link = $('a[href="#' + $(elm).attr('id') + '"]');
          if(link.data('toggle') === "tab") {
            link.tab("show");
          }
        });
      }
    };


    // Set the correct tab when the page loads
    showStuffFromHash(context);

    // Set the correct tab when a user uses their back/forward button
    $(window).on('hashchange', function() {
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    // Change the URL when tabs are clicked
    $('a', context).on('click', function(e) {
      history.pushState(null, null, this.href);
      showStuffFromHash(context);
    });

    return this;
  };
}(jQuery));

window.buildTabsets = function(tocID) {

  // build a tabset from a section div with the .tabset class
  function buildTabset(tabset) {

    // check for fade and pills options
    var fade = tabset.hasClass("tabset-fade");
    var pills = tabset.hasClass("tabset-pills");
    var navClass = pills ? "nav-pills" : "nav-tabs";

    // determine the heading level of the tabset and tabs
    var match = tabset.attr('class').match(/level(\d) /);
    if (match === null)
      return;
    var tabsetLevel = Number(match[1]);
    var tabLevel = tabsetLevel + 1;

    // find all subheadings immediately below
    var tabs = tabset.find("div.section.level" + tabLevel);
    if (!tabs.length)
      return;

    // create tablist and tab-content elements
    var tabList = $('<ul class="nav ' + navClass + '" role="tablist"></ul>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabList);
    var tabContent = $('<div class="tab-content"></div>');
    $(tabs[0]).before(tabContent);

    // build the tabset
    var activeTab = 0;
    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>

<style type="text/css">
img.leaflet-tile {
padding: 0;
margin: 0;
border-radius: 0;
border: none;
}
.info {
padding: 6px 8px;
font: 14px/16px Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
background: white;
background: rgba(255,255,255,0.8);
box-shadow: 0 0 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
border-radius: 5px;
}
.legend {
line-height: 18px;
color: #555;
}
.legend svg text {
fill: #555;
}
.legend svg line {
stroke: #555;
}
.legend i {
width: 18px;
height: 18px;
margin-right: 4px;
opacity: 0.7;
display: inline-block;
vertical-align: top;

zoom: 1;
*display: inline;
}
</style>

<div id="introduction" class="section level1" number="1">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">1</span> Introduction</h1>
<p>The goal of this project is to determine the relationship between
commuting to Wallonia communes as a dependent variable and life
expectancy, age average, unemployment rate, percentage of non-Belgians,
and total population in 2013.</p>
<p>First, collect all of the libraries that are required for this
project.</p>

<div id="the-commute-between-wallinias-commune-in-2013" class="section level3" number="1.1.6">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">1.1.6</span> The commute between
Wallinias commune in 2013</h3>
<p>According to my project goal, the difference between zone out and
zone in gives me the net number of people who commute to another
commune for work.As previously stated, This variable is determined as a
dependence variable.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb12"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb12-1"><a href="#cb12-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Wa_commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">read.csv</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Data/Commute2013.csv&quot;</span>,<span class="at">header =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>,</span>
<span id="cb12-2"><a href="#cb12-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                     <span class="at">sep =</span> <span class="st">&quot;,&quot;</span>,<span class="at">quote =</span> <span class="st">&quot;</span><span class="sc">\&quot;</span><span class="st">&quot;</span>,<span class="at">dec=</span><span class="st">&quot;,&quot;</span>,<span class="at">fill =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>,<span class="at">comment.char =</span> <span class="st">&quot;&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb12-3"><a href="#cb12-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>wa_commute262<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">data.frame</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Code_INS&quot;</span><span class="ot">=</span>WID,<span class="st">&quot;Out&quot;</span><span class="ot">=</span><span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="st">&quot;In&quot;</span><span class="ot">=</span><span class="dv">0</span>)</span>
<span id="cb12-4"><a href="#cb12-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Creating a data frame for the net zone out of commute with a shared field for merging to a shapefile and an independence variable</span></span>
<span id="cb12-5"><a href="#cb12-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="cf">for</span> (i <span class="cf">in</span> WID){</span>
<span id="cb12-6"><a href="#cb12-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  wa_commute262[wa_commute262<span class="sc">$</span>Code_INS<span class="sc">==</span>i,<span class="st">&quot;Out&quot;</span>]<span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sum</span>(Wa_commute[Wa_commute<span class="sc">$</span>zonout<span class="sc">==</span>i,<span class="st">&quot;mouv&quot;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb12-7"><a href="#cb12-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>  wa_commute262[wa_commute262<span class="sc">$</span>Code_INS<span class="sc">==</span>i,<span class="st">&quot;In&quot;</span>]<span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">sum</span>(Wa_commute[Wa_commute<span class="sc">$</span>zonin<span class="sc">==</span>i,<span class="st">&quot;mouv&quot;</span>])</span>
<span id="cb12-8"><a href="#cb12-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb12-9"><a href="#cb12-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>wa_commute262<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>wa_commute262<span class="sc">$</span>Out<span class="sc">-</span>wa_commute262<span class="sc">$</span>In</span></code></pre></div>
</div>

<pre><code>## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: &quot;E:\Geography and spatial planning\summer semester 2022\Exploratory Spatial Data Analysis and Geostatistics (track B)\Final\R_Final\Data\Walcom.shp&quot;, layer: &quot;Walcom&quot;
## with 262 features
## It has 10 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  IDCOM NEWFIELD1 ARR</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb16"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb16-1"><a href="#cb16-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(Wallonie_sp,<span class="at">col=</span><span class="st">&quot;pink&quot;</span>, <span class="at">main =</span> <span class="st">&#39;Communes of Wallonie region&#39;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb17"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb17-1"><a href="#cb17-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="do">## the important part is &quot;projection&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb17-2"><a href="#cb17-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">proj4string</span>(Wallonie_sp) <span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">CRS</span>(<span class="st">&quot;+init=epsg:31300&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
</div>

<div id="cleaning-the-data" class="section level2" number="1.2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">1.2</span> Cleaning the
data</h2>
<p>In this subchapter, as a cleaning data base, focus on providing data
with some function that contains all the data required for analysis.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb18"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb18-1"><a href="#cb18-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#mereg the shape file with independence and dependence variable</span></span>

<div class="sourceCode" id="cb20"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb20-1"><a href="#cb20-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>choro <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="cf">function</span>(shp, variable,cls,rang) {</span>
<span id="cb20-2"><a href="#cb20-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>var <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">round</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data[, variable], <span class="at">digits =</span> <span class="dv">2</span>)</span>
<span id="cb20-3"><a href="#cb20-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>breaks <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">classIntervals</span>(var, <span class="at">n =</span> cls, <span class="at">style =</span> <span class="st">&quot;fisher&quot;</span>)<span class="sc">$</span>brk</span>
<span id="cb20-4"><a href="#cb20-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>my_colours <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">brewer.pal</span>(cls, rang)</span>
<span id="cb20-5"><a href="#cb20-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(shp, <span class="at">col =</span> my_colours[<span class="fu">findInterval</span>(var, breaks, <span class="at">all.inside =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>)],</span>
<span id="cb20-6"><a href="#cb20-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="at">axes =</span> <span class="cn">FALSE</span>, <span class="at">border =</span> <span class="fu">rgb</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="fl">0.8</span>, <span class="fl">0.8</span>))</span>
<span id="cb20-7"><a href="#cb20-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">invisible</span>(<span class="fu">list</span>(<span class="at">b =</span> breaks, <span class="at">c =</span> my_colours))</span>
<span id="cb20-8"><a href="#cb20-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>}</span>
<span id="cb20-9"><a href="#cb20-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>breaks <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">choro</span>(Wa_sp_01, <span class="st">&quot;chomage_15_64_2013&quot;</span>,<span class="dv">8</span>,<span class="st">&quot;RdPu&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb20-10"><a href="#cb20-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">legend</span>(<span class="at">x =</span> <span class="dv">17991</span>, <span class="at">y =</span> <span class="dv">109072</span>, <span class="at">legend =</span> <span class="fu">leglabs</span>(breaks<span class="sc">$</span>b), <span class="at">fill =</span> breaks<span class="sc">$</span>c, <span class="at">bty =</span> <span class="st">&quot;n&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb20-11"><a href="#cb20-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">title</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Unemployment rate in 2013 for Wallonie&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>

descriptive statistics</h3>

commune in Wallonias Regoin. The remaining six variables have integer
values and provide data on Net out, chomage_15_64 2013 (total
unemployment rate), Total population 2013, Part non belges 2013,

observations, the Net out shows the difference between zone Out and zone
In is available for all municipalities in 2013.</p>

<div class="sourceCode" id="cb31"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb31-1"><a href="#cb31-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">boxplot</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013, <span class="at">main =</span> <span class="st">&quot;the non_BEL in 2013&quot;</span>, <span class="at">range =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="at">border =</span> <span class="st">&#39;pink&#39;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb31-2"><a href="#cb31-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">points</span>(<span class="fu">mean</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013), <span class="at">col =</span> <span class="dv">1</span>, <span class="at">pch =</span> <span class="dv">19</span>)</span></code></pre></div>

<div class="sourceCode" id="cb32"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb32-1"><a href="#cb32-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">boxplot</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013 , <span class="at">main =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Age_mean2013&quot;</span>, <span class="at">range =</span> <span class="dv">0</span>, <span class="at">border =</span> <span class="st">&#39;pink&#39;</span>)</span>

### Considering the normality of the net zone out</p>
<p>There is no normal distribution in the histogram and Q-Q plot for net
zoning out. At an alpha of 0.01 percent, the Shapiro test has a very
small p value of 2.2e-16. So, indicating that it does not have a normal
distribution.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb33"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb33-1"><a href="#cb33-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">hist</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out,<span class="at">breaks=</span><span class="dv">50</span>,<span class="at">main=</span><span class="st">&quot;Net_Out&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb34"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb34-1"><a href="#cb34-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">qqnorm</span>(<span class="fu">scale</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out))</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb35"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb35-1"><a href="#cb35-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">shapiro.test</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test

## data:  Wa_sp_01$Net_out
## W = 0.49027, p-value &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="bivariate-descriptive-statistics" class="section level3" number="2.1.2">

descriptive statistics</h3>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb37"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb37-1"><a href="#cb37-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out,Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013, <span class="at">col =</span> <span class="fu">topo.colors</span>(<span class="dv">90</span>, .<span class="dv">2</span>)[<span class="dv">10</span>],</span>
<span id="cb37-2"><a href="#cb37-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>     <span class="at">pch =</span> <span class="dv">19</span>,<span class="at">xlab=</span><span class="st">&quot;Net_out&quot;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb37-3"><a href="#cb37-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>     <span class="at">ylab=</span><span class="st">&quot;Total_population_2013&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>

## Spatial autocorrelation and spatial regression</p>
<p>In this part,the aim was consideration of Spatial

</div>
</div>
<div id="spatial-autocorrelation" class="section level2" number="2.2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">2.2</span> Spatial
Autocorrelation</h2>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb38"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb38-1"><a href="#cb38-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Computing Local Morans I</span></span>
<span id="cb38-2"><a href="#cb38-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>coordWa<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">coordinates</span>(Wa_sp_01)</span>
<span id="cb38-3"><a href="#cb38-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#contQWa&lt;-poly2nb(Wa_sp_01)</span></span>
<span id="cb38-4"><a href="#cb38-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Wa_kn8<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">knn2nb</span>(<span class="fu">knearneigh</span>(coordWa,<span class="at">k=</span><span class="dv">8</span>))</span>
<span id="cb38-5"><a href="#cb38-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#cont_WM&lt;- nb2listw(contQWa_sp_01,zero.policy = TRUE)</span></span>
<span id="cb38-6"><a href="#cb38-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>kn8_WM<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">nb2listw</span>(Wa_kn8)</span></code></pre></div>
<div id="moran-test-of-the-independent-variable" class="section level3" number="2.2.1">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">2.2.1</span> Moran test of the
independent variable</h3>
<p>I&lt;0 -&gt; negative spatial autocorrelation, So it means that the
variable of unemployment rate is significantly spatially dispersed,is
not significantly different from zero. (Alpha=1%).</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb39"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb39-1"><a href="#cb39-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>moranI_unemploymentrate<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">moran.test</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb39-2"><a href="#cb39-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>moranI_unemploymentrate</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013  
## weights: kn8_WM    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 0.067732, p-value = 0.473
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      -0.001862570      -0.003831418       0.000844964</code></pre>
<p>This plot illustrate almost the negetive autocorelation.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb41"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb41-1"><a href="#cb41-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">moran.plot</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
### Local Moran (LISA) for dependent variable</p>
<p>LISA (or Local Moran) is the result of the lag and the variable
itself (normalized). LISA values can be easily determined using the
Moran scatterplot.The red color shows high and blue color shows low
souurounded with the same value of neighbourhood.So, The red color
represents high and the blue color represents low value that
surroundings with the neighborhood with same value.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb42"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb42-1"><a href="#cb42-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>dev_unemploymentrate<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013<span class="sc">-</span><span class="fu">mean</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013) <span class="co">#express variable as deviation to mean</span></span>
<span id="cb42-2"><a href="#cb42-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">lag.listw</span>(kn8_WM,dev_unemploymentrate) <span class="co">#lag the deviation to mean</span></span>
<span id="cb42-3"><a href="#cb42-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm &lt;- lm(spatial_lag_dev_x ~ dev_x)</span></span>
<span id="cb42-4"><a href="#cb42-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_itcpt&lt;- morlm$coefficients[1]</span></span>
<span id="cb42-5"><a href="#cb42-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_i &lt;- morlm$coefficients[2] #retrieves the slope</span></span>
<span id="cb42-6"><a href="#cb42-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_i</span></span>
<span id="cb42-7"><a href="#cb42-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lm_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">localmoran</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb42-8"><a href="#cb42-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">as.data.frame</span>(lm_dev_unemploymentrate)</span>
<span id="cb42-9"><a href="#cb42-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_dev_unemploymentrate <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">vector</span>(<span class="at">mode=</span><span class="st">&quot;numeric&quot;</span>,<span class="at">length=</span><span class="fu">length</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out))</span>
<span id="cb42-10"><a href="#cb42-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate <span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">1</span> <span class="co">#LL</span></span>
<span id="cb42-11"><a href="#cb42-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate <span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">2</span> <span class="co">#LH</span></span>
<span id="cb42-12"><a href="#cb42-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate <span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">3</span> <span class="co">#HL</span></span>
<span id="cb42-13"><a href="#cb42-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_dev_unemploymentrate[dev_unemploymentrate <span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span>spatial_lag_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">4</span> <span class="co">#HH</span></span>
<span id="cb42-14"><a href="#cb42-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb42-15"><a href="#cb42-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">$</span>quad<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>quad_dev_unemploymentrate</span>
<span id="cb42-16"><a href="#cb42-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># statistical significance level</span></span>
<span id="cb42-17"><a href="#cb42-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>signif <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fl">0.1</span></span>
<span id="cb42-18"><a href="#cb42-18" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb42-19"><a href="#cb42-19" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">$</span>signif_quad<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>quad_dev_unemploymentrate</span>
<span id="cb42-20"><a href="#cb42-20" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">$</span>signif_quad[lisa_dev_unemploymentrate[,<span class="dv">5</span>]<span class="sc">&gt;</span>signif]<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="dv">0</span></span>
<span id="cb42-21"><a href="#cb42-21" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb42-22"><a href="#cb42-22" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>brks <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>,<span class="dv">4</span>)</span>
<span id="cb42-23"><a href="#cb42-23" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>colorsLISA <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;white&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;blue&quot;</span>,<span class="fu">rgb</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="at">alpha=</span><span class="fl">0.4</span>),<span class="fu">rgb</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="at">alpha=</span><span class="fl">0.4</span>),<span class="st">&quot;red&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb42-24"><a href="#cb42-24" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>colorsLISA_each<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>colorsLISA[<span class="fu">findInterval</span>(lisa_dev_unemploymentrate<span class="sc">$</span>signif_quad,brks,<span class="at">all.inside=</span><span class="cn">FALSE</span>)]</span>
<span id="cb42-25"><a href="#cb42-25" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(Wa_sp_01,<span class="at">border=</span><span class="st">&quot;lightgray&quot;</span>,<span class="at">col=</span>colorsLISA_each)</span>
<span id="cb42-26"><a href="#cb42-26" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">box</span>()</span>
<span id="cb42-27"><a href="#cb42-27" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">legend</span>(<span class="st">&quot;bottomright&quot;</span>, <span class="at">legend=</span><span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;insignificant&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;low-low&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;low-high&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;high-low&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;high-high&quot;</span>),</span>
<span id="cb42-28"><a href="#cb42-28" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>       <span class="at">fill=</span>colorsLISA,</span>
<span id="cb42-29"><a href="#cb42-29" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>       <span class="at">bty=</span><span class="st">&quot;n&quot;</span>, <span class="at">cex=</span><span class="fl">0.7</span>,<span class="at">y.intersp=</span><span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="at">x.intersp=</span><span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb42-30"><a href="#cb42-30" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb42-31"><a href="#cb42-31" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">title</span>(<span class="fu">paste</span>(<span class="st">&quot;LISA Cluster Map&quot;</span>, signif))</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
### Morans I test for dependent variable Significant negetive spatial
autocorrelation in the independence variable,</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb43"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb43-1"><a href="#cb43-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>moranI_commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">moran.test</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb43-2"><a href="#cb43-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>moranI_commute</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  Wa_sp_01$Net_out  
## weights: kn8_WM    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = -0.94409, p-value = 0.8274
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##     -0.0288386454     -0.0038314176      0.0007016226</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb45"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb45-1"><a href="#cb45-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">moran.plot</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb46"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb46-1"><a href="#cb46-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>dev_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out<span class="sc">-</span><span class="fu">mean</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out) <span class="co">#express variable as deviation to mean</span></span>
<span id="cb46-2"><a href="#cb46-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">lag.listw</span>(kn8_WM,dev_Commute) <span class="co">#lag the deviation to mean</span></span>
<span id="cb46-3"><a href="#cb46-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm &lt;- lm(spatial_lag_dev_x ~ dev_x)</span></span>
<span id="cb46-4"><a href="#cb46-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_itcpt&lt;- morlm$coefficients[1]</span></span>
<span id="cb46-5"><a href="#cb46-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_i &lt;- morlm$coefficients[2] #retrieves the slope</span></span>
<span id="cb46-6"><a href="#cb46-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_i</span></span>
<span id="cb46-7"><a href="#cb46-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lm_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">localmoran</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb46-8"><a href="#cb46-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">as.data.frame</span>(lm_Commute)</span>
<span id="cb46-9"><a href="#cb46-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">vector</span>(<span class="at">mode=</span><span class="st">&quot;numeric&quot;</span>,<span class="at">length=</span><span class="fu">length</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out))</span>
<span id="cb46-10"><a href="#cb46-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">1</span> <span class="co">#LL</span></span>
<span id="cb46-11"><a href="#cb46-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">2</span> <span class="co">#LH</span></span>
<span id="cb46-12"><a href="#cb46-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">3</span> <span class="co">#HL</span></span>
<span id="cb46-13"><a href="#cb46-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span>spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">4</span> <span class="co">#HH</span></span>
<span id="cb46-14"><a href="#cb46-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb46-15"><a href="#cb46-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_Commute<span class="sc">$</span>quad<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>quad_Commute</span>
<span id="cb46-16"><a href="#cb46-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># statistical significance level</span></span>

<div id="lisa-map-in-significant-different-level" class="section level3" number="2.2.2">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">2.2.2</span> Lisa map in
significant different level</h3>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb49"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb49-1"><a href="#cb49-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>knitr<span class="sc">::</span><span class="fu">include_graphics</span>(<span class="st">&#39;lisanimCommute.gif&#39;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/gif;base64," /><!-- --> ### Checking for normality
and multi-collinearity</p>
<p>The Shapiro-Wilk normality test should result p &gt; 0.05 for the
distribution to be normal. The command cor allows for the calculation of
the Pearson Correlation Coefficients.so, p-value &lt; 2.2e-16 shows that
the the distribution is not normal.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb50"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb50-1"><a href="#cb50-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>dep_var<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out</span>
<span id="cb50-2"><a href="#cb50-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>expl_vars<span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">data.frame</span>(<span class="at">Wa_pop=</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013,<span class="at">Wa_unemp=</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013,<span class="at">Wa_age=</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013,<span class="at">Wa_NonBelges=</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013,</span>
<span id="cb50-3"><a href="#cb50-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="at">Wa_life=</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>e0_.ans.)</span>
<span id="cb50-4"><a href="#cb50-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb50-5"><a href="#cb50-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">shapiro.test</span>(dep_var)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  dep_var
## W = 0.49027, p-value &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<p>we use the corrgram and VIFfor checking the multi-collinearity
between variable. No evidence of multicollinearity between all
independent variables.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb52"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb52-1"><a href="#cb52-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">corrgram</span>(expl_vars,<span class="at">upper.panel =</span> panel.cor, <span class="at">cor.method =</span> <span class="st">&quot;pearson&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb53"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb53-1"><a href="#cb53-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>model_01<span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">lm</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out<span class="sc">~</span> Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>e0_.ans.,<span class="at">na.action =</span> na.omit)</span>
<span id="cb53-2"><a href="#cb53-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Testing for multicollinearity issues</span></span>
<span id="cb53-3"><a href="#cb53-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">vif</span>(model_01) </span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>##    Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013 Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 
##                       1.052264                       1.164376 
##         Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013  Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013 
##                       1.052761                       1.141730 
##              Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans. 
##                       1.024201</code></pre>
</div>
</div>
<div id="ordinary-least-squares-ols-model" class="section level2" number="2.3">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">2.3</span> Ordinary
least-squares (OLS) model</h2>
<p>According to this model, the unemployment rate, age average, and life
expectancy have no significant impact at the confidence level of
95%.And, the total population has a significant impact at the confidence
level of 99%.</p>
<p>According to the coefficients of the model, we can say that: by
having controll on other variables when he population increases by 1
unit, the difference between zoning out and zoning in Wallonias commune
decrease by 1.122e-01.</p>
<p>Also, by having controll on other variables when the percentage of
non_Belgian increases by 1 %, the difference between zoning out and
zoning in Wallonias commune increase by 5.682e+01.</p>
<p>as well as this model The considered (and significant) variables
explain approximately 58 percent of net zoning out.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb55"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb55-1"><a href="#cb55-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>model_01<span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">lm</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out<span class="sc">~</span> Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>chomage_15_64_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>e0_.ans.,<span class="at">na.action =</span> na.omit)</span>
<span id="cb55-2"><a href="#cb55-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">summary</span>(model_01)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Wa_sp_01$Net_out ~ Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013 + 
##     Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 + Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 + 
##     Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 + Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013 + 
##     Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans., na.action = na.omit)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -8600.8  -910.3  -224.2   977.6  6551.6 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                                  Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(&gt;|t|)    
## (Intercept)                     6.718e+03  8.462e+03   0.794   0.4280    
## Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013     1.723e+01  2.666e+01   0.646   0.5187    
## Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 -1.122e-01  6.134e-03 -18.299   &lt;2e-16 ***
## Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013          1.494e+02  7.859e+01   1.901   0.0584 .  
## Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013   5.682e+01  2.251e+01   2.524   0.0122 *  
## Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans.              -1.400e+02  9.572e+01  -1.463   0.1448    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 &#39;***&#39; 0.001 &#39;**&#39; 0.01 &#39;*&#39; 0.05 &#39;.&#39; 0.1 &#39; &#39; 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1936 on 256 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.5876, Adjusted R-squared:  0.5796 
## F-statistic: 72.96 on 5 and 256 DF,  p-value: &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb57"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb57-1"><a href="#cb57-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Diagnostic plot</span></span>
<span id="cb57-2"><a href="#cb57-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">par</span>(<span class="at">mfrow=</span><span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>)) <span class="co">#plot layout</span></span>
<span id="cb57-3"><a href="#cb57-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(model_01)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
# Testing for residuals heteroskedasticity</p>
<p>The Pvalue shows that Homoskedasticity assumption rejected!</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb58"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb58-1"><a href="#cb58-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Testing for residuals heteroskedasticity</span></span>
<span id="cb58-2"><a href="#cb58-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb58-3"><a href="#cb58-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>bptest<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">bptest</span>(model_01)</span>
<span id="cb58-4"><a href="#cb58-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">print</span>(bptest)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  model_01
## BP = 99.26, df = 5, p-value &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="spatial-dependence-tests" class="section level2" number="2.4">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">2.4</span> Spatial dependence
tests</h2>
<p>In the presence of spatial dependence, the results of Ordinary Least
Squares estimation are skewed. As a result, the aim was the considering
spatial potential indirect effects on the dependent variables, which
were previously redacted from the linear regression.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb60"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb60-1"><a href="#cb60-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Mapping residuals</span></span>
<span id="cb60-2"><a href="#cb60-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Add the residuals to the spatial dataframe</span></span>
<span id="cb60-3"><a href="#cb60-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>residmodel_0<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">resid</span>(model_01)</span></code></pre></div>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb61"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb61-1"><a href="#cb61-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Plot residuals</span></span>
<span id="cb61-2"><a href="#cb61-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>resOLS<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">resid</span>(model_01)</span>
<span id="cb61-3"><a href="#cb61-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb61-4"><a href="#cb61-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">spplot</span>(Wa_sp_01,<span class="at">zcol=</span><span class="st">&quot;resOLS&quot;</span>,<span class="at">col.regions=</span><span class="fu">colorRampPalette</span>(<span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;gray&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;pink&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;purple&quot;</span>))(<span class="dv">262</span>))</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
No significant spatial autocorrelation in the residuals</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb62"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb62-1"><a href="#cb62-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#Computing Local Morans I of OLS residuals</span></span>
<span id="cb62-2"><a href="#cb62-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>moranI_resOLS<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">moran.test</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>resOLS,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb62-3"><a href="#cb62-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>moranI_resOLS</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Moran I test under randomisation
## 
## data:  Wa_sp_01$resOLS  
## weights: kn8_WM    
## 
## Moran I statistic standard deviate = 3.4153, p-value = 0.0003186
## alternative hypothesis: greater
## sample estimates:
## Moran I statistic       Expectation          Variance 
##      0.0948962020     -0.0038314176      0.0008356497</code></pre>

<div id="local-moran-and-lisa-cluster-map" class="section level2" number="2.5">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">2.5</span> Local Moran and LISA
Cluster Map</h2>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb65"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb65-1"><a href="#cb65-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>dev_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>resOLS<span class="sc">-</span><span class="fu">mean</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>resOLS) <span class="co">#express variable as deviation to mean</span></span>
<span id="cb65-2"><a href="#cb65-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">lag.listw</span>(kn8_WM,dev_Commute) <span class="co">#lag the deviation to mean</span></span>
<span id="cb65-3"><a href="#cb65-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm &lt;- lm(spatial_lag_dev_x ~ dev_x)</span></span>
<span id="cb65-4"><a href="#cb65-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_itcpt&lt;- morlm$coefficients[1]</span></span>
<span id="cb65-5"><a href="#cb65-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_i &lt;- morlm$coefficients[2] #retrieves the slope</span></span>
<span id="cb65-6"><a href="#cb65-6" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#morlm_i</span></span>
<span id="cb65-7"><a href="#cb65-7" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lm_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">localmoran</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>resOLS,<span class="at">listw =</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb65-8"><a href="#cb65-8" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_Commute<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">as.data.frame</span>(lm_Commute)</span>
<span id="cb65-9"><a href="#cb65-9" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">vector</span>(<span class="at">mode=</span><span class="st">&quot;numeric&quot;</span>,<span class="at">length=</span><span class="fu">length</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>resOLS))</span>
<span id="cb65-10"><a href="#cb65-10" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">1</span> <span class="co">#LL</span></span>
<span id="cb65-11"><a href="#cb65-11" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">2</span> <span class="co">#LH</span></span>
<span id="cb65-12"><a href="#cb65-12" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span> spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&lt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">3</span> <span class="co">#HL</span></span>
<span id="cb65-13"><a href="#cb65-13" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>quad_Commute[dev_Commute <span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span> <span class="sc">&amp;</span>spatial_lag_dev_Commute<span class="sc">&gt;</span><span class="dv">0</span>] <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="dv">4</span> <span class="co">#HH</span></span>
<span id="cb65-14"><a href="#cb65-14" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb65-15"><a href="#cb65-15" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_Commute<span class="sc">$</span>quad<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>quad_Commute</span>
<span id="cb65-16"><a href="#cb65-16" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co"># statistical significance level</span></span>
<span id="cb65-17"><a href="#cb65-17" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>signif <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fl">0.1</span></span>
<span id="cb65-18"><a href="#cb65-18" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb65-19"><a href="#cb65-19" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_Commute<span class="sc">$</span>signif_quad<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>quad_Commute</span>
<span id="cb65-20"><a href="#cb65-20" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>lisa_Commute<span class="sc">$</span>signif_quad[lisa_Commute[,<span class="dv">5</span>]<span class="sc">&gt;</span>signif]<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="dv">0</span></span>
<span id="cb65-21"><a href="#cb65-21" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb65-22"><a href="#cb65-22" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>brks <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">2</span>,<span class="dv">3</span>,<span class="dv">4</span>)</span>
<span id="cb65-23"><a href="#cb65-23" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>colorsLISA <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;white&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;blue&quot;</span>,<span class="fu">rgb</span>(<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="at">alpha=</span><span class="fl">0.4</span>),<span class="fu">rgb</span>(<span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="dv">0</span>,<span class="at">alpha=</span><span class="fl">0.4</span>),<span class="st">&quot;red&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb65-24"><a href="#cb65-24" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>colorsLISA_each<span class="ot">&lt;-</span>colorsLISA[<span class="fu">findInterval</span>(lisa_Commute<span class="sc">$</span>signif_quad,brks,<span class="at">all.inside=</span><span class="cn">FALSE</span>)]</span>
<span id="cb65-25"><a href="#cb65-25" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(Wa_sp_01,<span class="at">border=</span><span class="st">&quot;lightgray&quot;</span>,<span class="at">col=</span>colorsLISA_each)</span>
<span id="cb65-26"><a href="#cb65-26" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">box</span>()</span>
<span id="cb65-27"><a href="#cb65-27" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">legend</span>(<span class="st">&quot;bottomright&quot;</span>, <span class="at">legend=</span><span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;insignificant&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;low-low&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;low-high&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;high-low&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;high-high&quot;</span>),</span>
<span id="cb65-28"><a href="#cb65-28" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>       <span class="at">fill=</span>colorsLISA,</span>
<span id="cb65-29"><a href="#cb65-29" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>       <span class="at">bty=</span><span class="st">&quot;n&quot;</span>, <span class="at">cex=</span><span class="fl">0.7</span>,<span class="at">y.intersp=</span><span class="dv">1</span>,<span class="at">x.intersp=</span><span class="dv">1</span>)</span>
<span id="cb65-30"><a href="#cb65-30" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a></span>
<span id="cb65-31"><a href="#cb65-31" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">title</span>(<span class="fu">paste</span>(<span class="st">&quot;LISA Cluster Map&quot;</span>, signif))</span></code></pre></div>

<div id="spatial-chractrestic-of-variable" class="section level1" number="3">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">3</span> spatial chractrestic of
variable</h1>
<p>there is two way for considering the results of the Morans I test on
the dependent variable: 1.spatial dependency 2.spatial heterogeneity</p>
<div id="lagrange-multiplier-diagnostics-for-spatial-dependence" class="section level2" number="3.1">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">3.1</span> Lagrange multiplier
diagnostics for spatial dependence</h2>
<p>LMerr = 10.249, df = 1, p-value = 0.001367&gt; p-value is smaller
than alpha=0.01, This result demonstrates that the two Moran I result
tests are correct. and residuals are spatially dependent.</p>
<p>RLMerr = 32.655, df = 1, p-value = 1.1e-08&gt; p-value is smaller
than alpha=0.01.So, there is spatialy dependency in errors.</p>
<p>LMlag = 1.865, df = 1, p-value = 0.172&gt; p-value is larger than
alpha=0.01.So, there is not a spatial dependency.</p>
<p>RLMlag = 24.271, df = 1, p-value = 8.369e-07&gt;p-value is larger
than alpha=0.01.So,there is not a spatial dependency in errors.</p>
<p>SARMA = 34.52, df = 2, p-value = 3.192e-08&gt;p-value is larger
than alpha=0.01.So,there is not a spatial dependency.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb66"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb66-1"><a href="#cb66-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>LMOLS <span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">lm.LMtests</span>(model_01,kn8_WM,<span class="at">test=</span><span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;LMerr&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;RLMerr&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;LMlag&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;RLMlag&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;SARMA&quot;</span>),<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb66-2"><a href="#cb66-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>LMOLS</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  Lagrange multiplier diagnostics for spatial dependence
## 
## data:  
## model: lm(formula = Wa_sp_01$Net_out ~ Wa_sp_01$chomage_15_64_2013 +
## Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 + Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 +

## Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 + Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 +

## Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans., na.action = na.omit)
## weights: kn8_WM
## 
## RLMerr = 32.655, df = 1, p-value = 1.1e-08
##

## Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 + Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 +
## Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 + Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013 +
## Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans., na.action = na.omit)
## weights: kn8_WM
## 
## LMlag = 1.865, df = 1, p-value = 0.172
## 
## 
##  Lagrange multiplier diagnostics for spatial dependence
##

(SEM)</h3>
<p>p value for Lambda is 0.0004954, indicating that the spatial
dependence test results show significant spatial error dependence.(It is
less than alpha=0.01)</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb68"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb68-1"><a href="#cb68-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>SEM <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">errorsarlm</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out<span class="sc">~</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>e0_.ans., <span class="at">listw=</span>kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T )</span>

<div id="testing-for-residuals-heteroskedasticity" class="section level1" number="4">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">4</span> Testing for residuals
heteroskedasticity:</h1>
<p>The Pvalue shows that Homoskedasticity assumption rejected!</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb70"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb70-1"><a href="#cb70-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">bptest.Sarlm</span>(SEM)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
##  studentized Breusch-Pagan test
## 
## data:  
## BP = 92.42, df = 4, p-value &lt; 2.2e-16</code></pre>
<div id="spatial-autoregressive-model-sar" class="section level3" number="4.0.1">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">4.0.1</span> Spatial
autoregressive model (SAR)</h3>
<p>[Rho= -0.16065] shows that not Significant and negetive spatial lag
parameter. there is not Spatial dependence test on SAR residuals now
identify significant spatial error dependence! (in line with LM-test!)
In this model compared to the OLS model, the variables of total
population and presentage of non-Belgians are not significant. But the
negative relationship between total population and net zoning out is the
same in both models. as well as the posetive relationship with
presentage of non-Belgian.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb72"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb72-1"><a href="#cb72-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>SAR<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">lagsarlm</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out<span class="sc">~</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>e0_.ans., <span class="at">listw=</span> kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T)</span>
<span id="cb72-2"><a href="#cb72-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">summary</span>(SAR)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:lagsarlm(formula = Wa_sp_01$Net_out ~ Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 +

<div id="spatial-simultaneous-autoregressive-model-sac" class="section level3" number="4.0.2">

Simultaneous Autoregressive Model (SAC)</h3>
<ul>
<li>Not Significant error and lag parameter (do not confirms
LM-test)</li>
<li>Signs and significance of explanatory variables changed</li>
</ul>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb76"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb76-1"><a href="#cb76-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>SAC<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">sacsarlm</span>(Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Net_out <span class="sc">~</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Total_population_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013<span class="sc">+</span>Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>e0_.ans., <span class="at">listw=</span>kn8_WM,<span class="at">zero.policy =</span> T,<span class="at">listw2=</span><span class="cn">NULL</span>)</span>
<span id="cb76-2"><a href="#cb76-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">summary</span>(SAC)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## 
## Call:sacsarlm(formula = Wa_sp_01$Net_out ~ Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 + 
##     Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 + Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013 + Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013 + 
##     Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans., listw = kn8_WM, listw2 = NULL, zero.policy = T)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -7901.84  -798.45  -117.52   895.13  6753.43 
## 
## Type: sac 
## Coefficients: (asymptotic standard errors) 
##                                   Estimate  Std. Error  z value  Pr(&gt;|z|)
## (Intercept)                    -1.1401e+03  8.9904e+03  -0.1268  0.899084
## Wa_sp_01$Total_population_2013 -1.1367e-01  5.9921e-03 -18.9695 &lt; 2.2e-16
## Wa_sp_01$Age_moyen2013          1.8555e+02  6.8185e+01   2.7212  0.006504
## Wa_sp_01$Part_non_belges_2013   3.5538e+01  2.4465e+01   1.4526  0.146333
## Wa_sp_01$e0_.ans.              -5.2063e+01  1.0593e+02  -0.4915  0.623070
##

<div id="gwr-using-gwmodel" class="section level2" number="4.1">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.1</span> GWR using
GWModel</h2>
<p>GWR analyzes a local model of the parameter or method you are
attempting to comprehend or predict by connecting a regression model to
each feature in the dataset.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb82"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb82-1"><a href="#cb82-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>DepVar<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="st">&quot;Net_out&quot;</span></span>
<span id="cb82-2"><a href="#cb82-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>IndVars1<span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Total_population_2013&quot;</span>,<span class="st">&quot;chomage_15_64_2013&quot;</span> , <span class="st">&quot;Part_non_belges_2013&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;Age_moyen2013&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;e0_.ans.&quot;</span>)</span>
<span id="cb82-3"><a href="#cb82-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>model.sel <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">model.selection.gwr</span>(DepVar,IndVars1,<span class="at">data=</span>Wa_sp_01,<span class="at">kernel=</span><span class="st">&quot;bisquare&quot;</span>,<span class="at">adaptive =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>, <span class="at">bw=</span><span class="dv">20</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~chomage_15_64_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Part_non_belges_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Age_moyen2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~e0_.ans. 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+chomage_15_64_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Part_non_belges_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+e0_.ans. 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013+chomage_15_64_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013+Part_non_belges_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013+e0_.ans. 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013+Part_non_belges_2013+chomage_15_64_2013 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013+Part_non_belges_2013+e0_.ans. 
## Now calibrating the model: 
##  Net_out~Total_population_2013+Age_moyen2013+Part_non_belges_2013+e0_.ans.+chomage_15_64_2013</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb84"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb84-1"><a href="#cb84-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>sorted.models <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">model.sort.gwr</span>(model.sel, <span class="at">numVars =</span> <span class="fu">length</span>(IndVars1),</span>
<span id="cb84-2"><a href="#cb84-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="at">ruler.vector =</span> model.sel[[<span class="dv">2</span>]][,<span class="dv">2</span>])</span>
<span id="cb84-3"><a href="#cb84-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>model.list <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> sorted.models[[<span class="dv">1</span>]]</span>
<span id="cb84-4"><a href="#cb84-4" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="co">#X11(width = 12, height = 6)</span></span>
<span id="cb84-5"><a href="#cb84-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">model.view.gwr</span>(DepVar, IndVars1, <span class="at">model.list =</span> model.list)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb85"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb85-1"><a href="#cb85-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(sorted.models[[<span class="dv">2</span>]][,<span class="dv">2</span>], <span class="at">col =</span> <span class="st">&quot;black&quot;</span>, <span class="at">pch =</span> <span class="dv">20</span>, <span class="at">lty =</span> <span class="dv">5</span>,</span>
<span id="cb85-2"><a href="#cb85-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="at">main =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Alternative view of model selection procedure&quot;</span>,</span>
<span id="cb85-3"><a href="#cb85-3" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="at">ylab =</span> <span class="st">&quot;AICc&quot;</span>, <span class="at">xlab =</span> <span class="st">&quot;Model number&quot;</span>, <span class="at">type =</span> <span class="st">&quot;b&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
According to the above figures, we should choose model 15 because it has
the lowest AICc. We begin by determining the best bandwidth and then
match the basic local model:</p>

<span id="cb86-2"><a href="#cb86-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>    Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013 <span class="sc">+</span> Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Age_moyen2013 <span class="sc">+</span> Wa_sp_01<span class="sc">$</span>Part_non_belges_2013 <span class="sc">+</span> </span>

<span id="cb86-5"><a href="#cb86-5" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                <span class="at">kernel =</span> <span class="st">&quot;bisquare&quot;</span>, <span class="at">adaptive =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>)</span></code></pre></div>

<p>The lower AICc value in the local model (4685.144) than in the global
(OLS) model (4717.739), as well as the higher R-squared value in the
local model (0.57) than in the global (OLS) model (0.67), confirm the
existence of spatial variation in the relationships between two
variables.</p>

<div id="spatial-interaction-modelling---poisson-regression" class="section level2" number="4.3">

<div id="point-pattern" class="section level2" number="4.4">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.4</span> point pattern</h2>
<p>In this part the main aim is considering the point of child care
place in the Wallomia region as the point pattern.</p>
<div id="add-the-table-of-the-places" class="section level3" number="4.4.1">
<h3><span class="header-section-number">4.4.1</span> Add the table of
the places</h3>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb97"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb97-1"><a href="#cb97-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>child_care_places<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">read.csv</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Data/number of child-care places.csv&quot;</span>,<span class="at">header =</span> <span class="cn">TRUE</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p>this number shows the number of communes that determine the center of
each comune.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb98"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb98-1"><a href="#cb98-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">nrow</span>(child_care_places)</span></code></pre></div>
<pre><code>## [1] 262</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb100"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb100-1"><a href="#cb100-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">summary</span>(child_care_places)</span></code></pre></div>

<pre><code>## [1] &quot;data.frame&quot;</code></pre>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb104"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb104-1"><a href="#cb104-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>Wal.point_sp<span class="ot">&lt;-</span><span class="fu">readOGR</span>(<span class="st">&quot;Data/Wal.shp&quot;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>

<div class="sourceCode" id="cb108"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb108-1"><a href="#cb108-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a><span class="fu">plot</span>(child_care_places_sp, <span class="at">main =</span> <span class="st">&quot;The centre of Wallonia&#39;s communes &quot;</span>, <span class="at">col =</span> <span class="st">&#39;red&#39;</span>, <span class="at">pch =</span> <span class="st">&#39;*&#39;</span>)</span></code></pre></div>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" />
### The numbre of child_care places in Wallonia</p>
<p>In this section, the number of child care places is represented by a
circle. In addition, the size of the circle indicates the number of
places in each commune.</p>
<div class="sourceCode" id="cb109"><pre class="sourceCode r"><code class="sourceCode r"><span id="cb109-1"><a href="#cb109-1" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>colwa <span class="ot">&lt;-</span> <span class="fu">findColours</span>(<span class="fu">classIntervals</span>(child_care_places_sp1<span class="sc">@</span>data<span class="sc">$</span>Nombre_places2013, <span class="at">n =</span> <span class="dv">7</span>), </span>
<span id="cb109-2"><a href="#cb109-2" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1"></a>                        <span class="fu">c</span>(<span class="st">&quot;orange&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;purple&quot;</span>, <span class="st">&quot;red&quot;</span>)) <span class="co">#n=7 is the number of intervals</span></span>

<div id="conclusion" class="section level2" number="4.5">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.5</span> Conclusion</h2>
<p>In this project, the net zoning out of communes with the goal of
commuting was considered as an independence variable, and the
unemployment rate, average age, life expectancy, total population, and
percentage of non-Belgians in 2013 as a dependent variable.The total
population and the percentage of non-Belgians have an effect on the
independence variable in the OLS model.</p>
<p>According to the coefficients of the model, we can say that: by
having controll on other variables when he population increases by 1
unit, the difference between zoning out and zoning in Wallonias commune
decrease by 1.122e-01. Also, by having controll on other variables when
the percentage of non_Belgian increases by 1 %, the difference between
zoning out and zoning in Wallonias commune increase by 5.682e+01.</p>
<p>As a result, the percentage of non-Belgians has a positive
relationship with the independent variable, while the total population
has a negative relationship.</p>
<p>Significant spatial error dependence, significant spatial lag
dependence, and no significant spatial error dependence after accounting
for spatial lag dependence were discovered in spatial dependence.</p>
<p>The lower AICc value in the local model (4685.144) than in the global
(OLS) model (4717.739), as well as the higher R-squared value in the
local model (0.57) than in the global (OLS) model (0.67), confirm the
existence of spatial variation in the relationships between two
variables.</p>
<p>In the point pattern part the number of child care places is
represented by a circle. In addition, the size of the circle indicates
the number of places in each commune.(using leaflet for illustrating the
point in the certain place)</p>
